## Data flows in one direction

React has a fundamental rule: **data flows downward**. A parent component passes data to its children through props. Children never pass data back up to their parents directly. This is called **one-way data flow** or **unidirectional data flow**, and it is the single most important concept for understanding how React apps work.

Here is a concrete example:

```jsx
function App() {
  const currentUser = {
    name: "Jordan Rivera",
    email: "jordan@example.com",
    role: "Product Manager",
  };

  return (
    <div className="app">
      <Header userName={currentUser.name} />
      <Dashboard user={currentUser} />
      <Footer />
    </div>
  );
}
```

The `App` component owns the user data. It passes `currentUser.name` to `Header` and the entire `currentUser` object to `Dashboard`. `Footer` does not receive any user data -- it does not need it.

Now let us look at what `Header` does with its prop:

```jsx
function Header({ userName }) {
  return (
    <header className="site-header">
      <h1>My App</h1>
      <span className="user-greeting">Welcome, {userName}</span>
    </header>
  );
}
```

`Header` receives `userName` and displays it. It does not know where the name came from. It does not know about `currentUser.email` or `currentUser.role`. It only knows about the one prop it was given.

### Tracing data through multiple levels

In real apps, data often passes through several levels of components. Here is a three-level example:

```jsx
// Level 1: App owns the data
function App() {
  const user = { name: "Sarah", plan: "Pro", tasksCompleted: 47 };

  return (
    <div>
      <Dashboard user={user} />
    </div>
  );
}

// Level 2: Dashboard receives user and passes parts of it down
function Dashboard({ user }) {
  return (
    <div className="dashboard">
      <WelcomeMessage name={user.name} plan={user.plan} />
      <StatsPanel count={user.tasksCompleted} />
    </div>
  );
}

// Level 3: WelcomeMessage uses the data
function WelcomeMessage({ name, plan }) {
  return (
    <div className="welcome">
      <h2>Hello, {name}</h2>
      <p>Your current plan: {plan}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

// Level 3: StatsPanel uses the data
function StatsPanel({ count }) {
  return (
    <div className="stats">
      <p>Tasks completed: {count}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Trace the data flow:
1. `App` has the user object `{ name: "Sarah", plan: "Pro", tasksCompleted: 47 }`
2. `App` passes the entire object to `Dashboard` as the `user` prop
3. `Dashboard` unpacks the object and passes `user.name` and `user.plan` to `WelcomeMessage`, and `user.tasksCompleted` to `StatsPanel`
4. `WelcomeMessage` displays the name and plan. `StatsPanel` displays the count.

The user sees: **Hello, Sarah**, **Your current plan: Pro**, and **Tasks completed: 47**.

Notice how each component only receives the data it needs. `WelcomeMessage` does not know about `tasksCompleted`. `StatsPanel` does not know about `name` or `plan`. This is intentional -- it keeps each component focused.

### Prop drilling: when it gets messy

Sometimes data needs to pass through components that do not use it, just to reach a deeply nested child. This is called **prop drilling**, and it looks like this:

```jsx
function App() {
  const theme = "dark";

  return <Layout theme={theme} />;
}

function Layout({ theme }) {
  // Layout does not use theme -- it just passes it through
  return (
    <div className="layout">
      <Sidebar theme={theme} />
      <MainContent />
    </div>
  );
}

function Sidebar({ theme }) {
  // Sidebar does not use theme either -- passes it through again
  return (
    <aside>
      <NavMenu theme={theme} />
    </aside>
  );
}

function NavMenu({ theme }) {
  // NavMenu finally uses the theme
  return (
    <nav className={`nav-menu nav-${theme}`}>
      <a href="/home">Home</a>
      <a href="/settings">Settings</a>
    </nav>
  );
}
```

The `theme` prop passes through four levels: `App` -> `Layout` -> `Sidebar` -> `NavMenu`. Only `NavMenu` actually uses it. `Layout` and `Sidebar` are just passing it along.

This is called prop drilling because you are "drilling" the prop through layers of components. It works, but it has downsides:

- Every component in the chain has to declare and forward the prop
- If you rename the prop, you have to update every component in the chain
- It clutters components with props they do not use

Prop drilling is not a bug -- it is a code smell. When you see a prop passing through three or more levels without being used, that is a sign the codebase might benefit from a different pattern (you will learn about `useContext` in Level 3 as an alternative).

### Reading where data comes from

When you see a value displayed in a component and want to know where it comes from, work backwards:

1. **Find the value in the JSX.** Example: `<h2>{name}</h2>`
2. **Check if it is defined in the logic zone.** Is there a `const name = ...` above the return? If so, trace that value.
3. **Check if it is a prop.** Is `name` in the function parameter? If so, the value comes from the parent.
4. **Find the parent.** Look at the imports and search the codebase for where this component is used. The parent's code will show what value is passed for `name`.

This backward tracing is the most important debugging skill in React. When something displays the wrong value, the answer is somewhere in this chain.

### A realistic multi-component example

Here is a simplified e-commerce scenario:

```jsx
function ProductPage() {
  const product = {
    name: "Running Shoes",
    price: 89.99,
    description: "Lightweight and comfortable for daily runs.",
    inStock: true,
    reviews: 142,
  };

  return (
    <div className="product-page">
      <ProductHeader name={product.name} reviewCount={product.reviews} />
      <ProductDetails
        description={product.description}
        price={product.price}
        inStock={product.inStock}
      />
    </div>
  );
}

function ProductHeader({ name, reviewCount }) {
  return (
    <div className="product-header">
      <h1>{name}</h1>
      <span>{reviewCount} reviews</span>
    </div>
  );
}

function ProductDetails({ description, price, inStock }) {
  return (
    <div className="product-details">
      <p>{description}</p>
      <p className="price">${price}</p>
      <p className={inStock ? "in-stock" : "out-of-stock"}>
        {inStock ? "In Stock" : "Out of Stock"}
      </p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Notice how `ProductPage` splits its data across two child components. `ProductHeader` gets the name and review count. `ProductDetails` gets the description, price, and stock status. Neither child has access to data it does not need.

If you wanted to know why the product page shows "89.99" as the price, you would trace backward: `ProductDetails` displays `{price}` -> `price` is a prop -> `ProductPage` passes `price={product.price}` -> `product.price` is `89.99`.

